<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs Denounce U.N.-Authorized NATO Air Strikes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Serbs Denounce U.N.-Authorized NATO Air Strikes </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1204060394 Beijing XINHUA in English 0531 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1204060394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, April 11 (XINHUA) -- The Federal Republic 
of Yugoslavia and Serb leaders in former Yugoslavia today 
strongly denounced the U.N.-authorized NATO air strikes against 
Bosnian Serb positions, saying the world body had been directly 
involved in the civil war. 
  In an emergency government meeting called to discuss the 
latest developments in Bosnia, Yugoslav leaders said the United 
Nations, instead of disarming the Muslim forces in Gorazde, 
tolerated the two-week spring offensive against Serb-held 
positions launched by the Muslims in a systematic way. 
  When the Muslims were defeated in their spring offensive, 
the 
U.N. gave the go-ahead to launch air strikes on Serb positions 
under the pretext of the Muslim enclave of Gorazde being one of 
the U.N.- designated "safe areas," they said. 
  By authorizing NATO to launch air raids against Bosnian 
Serbs, the U.N. has been directly involved in the Bosnian war, 
the Yugoslav leader said, urging the world body to immediately 
renounce its "dangerous" policy of siding with the Muslims in 
the conflict. 
  NATO jets today launched a second air strike on Serb 
positions around Gorazde in less than 24 hours. According to 
U.N. military sources, Serb artillery, tank and machine gun fire 
into Gorazde town abated soon after NATO warplanes destroyed at 
least one Serb tank. 
  On Sunday [10 April], NATO war planes dropped three bombs on 
a Bosnian Serb command post controlling artillery attacks on 
Gorazde. The raid was the first time NATO has used air power on 
Serb forces attacking a U.N. "safe area" in Bosnia. 
  Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic said that by giving the 
go- ahead to NATO air strikes, the reputation of the world body 
as a mediator in the Bosnian peace process had been seriously 
impaired. 
  The NATO air raids also drew an angry response from Bosnian 
Serbs. 
  Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic called off a meeting 
planned for today with U.S. peace envoy Charles Redman, and one 
of his senior adviser threatened to take actions against U.N. 
peacekeeping troops and put the Serbs at war with the U.N. if 
NATO continued to launch air raids. 
  Momcilo Krajisnik, speaker of the Bosnian Serbs' parliament, 
said the air strikes showed that neither the U.S. nor the U.N. 
wanted peace in Bosnia. 
  The threat of air strikes forced the Serbs to withdraw their 
heavy artillery from besieged Sarajevo by February 20. Eight 
days later, NATO jets shot down four Serb war planes violating 
the U.N. declared no-fly zone over Bosnia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

