<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bosnian Envoy to U.S. Appeals to World </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bosnian Envoy to U.S. Appeals to World </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0904123894 Beijing XINHUA in English 1026 GMT 9 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0904123894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Istanbul, April 9 (XINHUA) -- Bosnia has warned that 
the unresolved conflicts in the country are threats to global 
peace. 
  The Bosnian ambassador to Washington, Necip Sacirbey, 
appealed Friday [8 April] at the four-day international 
conference on the Balkans to "the world not to tolerate what was 
happening in Bosnia." 
  The conference, which organized by the Solidarity Foundation 
of Turkey, is being held here from April 7 to 10, with 
participants from representatives from Austria, the United 
States, Britain, South Africa, Germany, Kuwait, Saudi Arabia and 
Malaysia. 
  "In the war in Bosnia," Sacirbey stated, "there are victims, 
aggressors, and observers. All of us are observers." 
  He asked that the observers not be passive, but to be just, 
and he appealed to them to remember Sarajevo, the capital city 
of Bosnia. 
  "Sarajevo is symbolic of the suffering of each group of 
people in today's world. When we are fighting for Sarajevo, we 
are fighting for a better tomorrow. Please help us," Sacirbey 
said. 
  Meanwhile, turkey Friday renewed a call to the Serbs to join 
the Bosnian-Croat Federation in Bosnia-Herzegovina, saying 
"Ankara is ready to do what it can." 
  Turkey, which shares cultural and religious ties with the 
Bosnian Moslems, has launched a series of diplomatic initiatives 
on use of force to stop the fighting in Bosnia. 
  Fighting broke out in Bosnia-Herzegovina in late February of 
1992 when 4.3 million population in the former Yugoslav republic 
voted for independence from Belgrade. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

