<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   NATO To Avoid Larger Conflict in Serbia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NATO To Avoid Larger Conflict in Serbia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1204042394 Beijing XINHUA in English 0310 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1204042394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn, April 11 (XINHUA) -- NATO Secretary General 
Manfred Woerner today said the western alliance will do its best 
to avoid involvement in a bigger conflict with the Bosnian Serbs. 
  In an interview with the No. 2 German television station 
ZDF, 
Woerner said that NATO does not intend to send ground troops to 
the region. 
  The NATO chief said the western alliance favors negotiations 
backed with "limited military actions" in hopes of giving a push 
to the negotiating process. 
  His statement came after NATO launched its second air raid 
earlier in the day on Serb positions around the U.N.-designated 
safe area of Gorazde in eastern Bosnia. 
  NATO bombed on Sunday and Monday Serb positions around the 
Muslim enclave in order to halt the Serb advance and protect 
U.N. personnel there from the Serb attackers. 
  U.N. special envoy for former Yugoslavia Yasushi Akashi, who 
authorized the two air strikes in less than 24 hours, warned 
Serbs of more air raids if they continue attacking Gorazde. 
  Woerner hoped the air strikes would produce "expected 
results" as was the case in Sarajevo, 
  Earlier this year, NATO succeeded in making Serbs withdraw 
their heavy weapons from around Sarajevo and lift the siege of 
the Bosnian capital by threatening air strikes against Serbs. 

</TEXT>

