<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Movement of UN Troops in Ex-Yugoslavia Restricted </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Movement of UN Troops in Ex-Yugoslavia Restricted </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1404045594 Beijing XINHUA in English 0447 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1404045594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, April 13 (XINHUA) -- The Federal Yugoslav 
government today decided, for the first time, to restrict the 
movements of the UN peacekeeping forces in the former Yugoslavia 
as of April 20. 
  The government said the peacekeeping forces must get visas 
before entering and staying in the Federal Yugoslavia and their 
vehicles must get approval before driving into the republic. 
  The Yugoslav government, which met today to discuss the 
question of cooperation with the UN peacekeeping forces, 
denounced them for calling in NATO war planes to launch air 
strikes against Bosnian Serb positions. 
  The government said that the UN peacekeeping forces ignored 
the Muslim forces' attempt to make use of the UN-designated 
"safe area" of Gorazde to attack the Serb positions. 
  It accused the UN peacekeeping forces of siding with the 
Muslims and being completely involved in the Bosnia civil war. 
  The government stressed that the UN and NATO actions will 
directly threaten the Bosnian peace process and could lead to 
escalation of the war. 

</TEXT>

