<H3> <TI>   Russia Favors Flexibility on Korean Nuclear Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russia Favors Flexibility on Korean Nuclear Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1404035294 Beijing XINHUA in English 0342 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1404035294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, April 13 (XINHUA) -- Russian Deputy Foreign 
Minister Aleksandr Panov said today that Russia would adopt "a 
flexible stand" in the effort to solve the nuclear issue on the 
Korean peninsula. 
  He suggested that the nuclear issue be resolved through 
bilateral negotiations or within the framework of the UN 
Security Council. 
  If both failed to work, then the possibility of an 
international conference should be explored, he said. 
  He added that China, Japan and South Korea did not oppose 
Russia's proposal for holding an international conference to 
guarantee the security and non-nuclear status of the Korean 
peninsula. 
  The Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) at present 
favors holding talks with the United States to find a solution 
to the nuclear issue. 
  Panov said that the DPRK nuclear issue should not be 
considered as only a bilateral question as it affects the 
international community, especially the neighboring nations of 
the Korean peninsula. 

</TEXT>

