<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Cites Perry on Bosnian Peace Negotiations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    XINHUA Cites Perry on Bosnian Peace Negotiations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1304191994 Beijing XINHUA in English 1754 GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1304191994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington, April 13 (XINHUA) -- U.S. Defense 
Secretary William Perry said here today he expected Serbs and 
Muslims in Bosnia to return to the negotiating table. 
  "That is our objective, that's the U.N. objective to see 
that 
cessation negotiated," Perry told ABC's program "Good Morning 
America." 
  U.S. F-16 fighter planes carried out air strikes against 
Serbian positions near the besieged Muslim enclave of Gorazde on 
Sunday [10 April] and Monday. 
  "We have to wait for a day or two to see what the Serbs' 
next 
action is," he noted, "if they start the shelling again, it is 
very likely that the United Nations will call for more air 
strikes and NATO will deliver those air strikes." 
  The United Nations has proclaimed that Gorazde is a safe 
haven and has put U.N. forces in there. 
  If the Serbs begin shelling at Gorazde again, Perry 
stressed, 
"the U.N. can invoke close air support to protect the U.N. 
forces." 
  Russia has denounced NATO air attacks against Bosnian Serbs 
and threatened to delay joining the NATO's partnership for peace. 
  Perry said that "I think the timing of their joining is not 
so important as the fact of joining." 
  He also said it is not necessary to consult with Russia on 
whether the U.N. should call for this strike because Russia 
agreed the U.N. resolution which allowed for the U.N. to call 
the strikes. 
  "So the United Nations' responsibility at that point was 
simply to invoke the action when it happened," he said, "you 
cannot have consultation in the middle of a close air support 
operation." 
  Asked what is the biggest national security problem for the 
United States, Perry said that "over the long term, the greatest 
problem, potential problem, is with Russia." 
  "If the reform movement should fail in Russia," the 
secretary 
claimed, "this would be a great catastrophe not only for Russia 
but for the whole world and for the United States security." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

