<F P=100> Sub-Saharan Africa </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rong Yiren Meets Qhobela </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rong Yiren Meets Qhobela </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1304102294 Beijing XINHUA in English 0917 GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1304102294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 13 (XINHUA) -- Vice-President Rong 
Yiren said here today that with joint efforts, the renewed 
Sino-Lesotho ties will be further consolidated and developed. 
  Extending a warm welcome to M.J. Qhobela, visiting foreign 
minister of the Kingdom of Lesotho, Rong described the visit as 
the first major contact between the two countries after they 
renewed diplomatic relations early this year. 
  The visit shows that the Lesotho Government pays attention 
to 
its relations with China, Rong said, adding he believes the 
visit will help enhance mutual understanding between the two 
peoples and the friendly cooperation between the two countries. 
  Rong appreciated the "one China" stance of the new Lesotho 
Government and its efforts to normalize bilateral relations. He 
thanked Qhobela for his contribution to the restoration of Sino- 
Lesotho ties. 
  China and Lesotho are both developing countries, Rong said. 
China holds that all countries, small or big, poor or rich, weak 
or strong, should live in equality and develop ties with one 
another on the basis of the five principles of peaceful 
co-existence. 
  Briefing Qhobela on China's domestic situation, Rong said 
that in the past decade and more, China has been pursuing a 
policy centered on economic construction, and its economic 
growth has been rapid. 
  Qhobela said the renewal of diplomatic ties between Lesotho 
and China is a historic event. Despite the long geographic 
distance, the two countries are linked together by common 
interests and the Lesotho-China ties have bright prospects, he 
said. 
  Qhobela told Rong that this was his 4th trip to China and 
that he and his party had witnessed great changes here. Lesotho 
will benefit from China's experience over the past decade, he 
said. 
  Qhobela and his party arrived here on April 10 as guests of 
Vice- Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen. 

</TEXT>

