<F P=100> East Europe </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Notes UN Report on East European Economies </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    XINHUA Notes UN Report on East European Economies </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0804053894 Beijing XINHUA in English 0510 GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0804053894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, April 7 (XINHUA) -- Most Eastern European 
nations are still in recession with little hope of a major 
recovery this year, a UN report issued today said. 
  The report from the UN Economic Commission for Europe (ECE) 
said the drop in production slowed down in most Eastern European 
nations and signs of recovery appeared even in a few countries 
of the region last year. 
  But considering the gravity of the recession, certain 
countries need a few more years to restore production to the 
pre-1989 level, the report added. 
  Production in Russia and other members of the Commonwealth 
of 
Independent States dropped by 13 percent in 1993 compared with 
20 percent in 1992, according to the report. 
  The ECE predicted that there is a very slim possibility of 
an 
end to the economic sliding in these countries this year. 
  The report also said the sharp rise of unemployment in 
Eastern European nations since 1991 has brought about serious 
social and economic problems in these countries. About 7.6 
million people had become jobless by the end of 1993, it added. 
  The commission stressed that the international aid to these 
countries at present cannot help solve the difficulties facing 
them. Eastern Europeans have become ever more disappointed over 
the huge gap between what has been promised and what has 
actually been given, it added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-2827 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi072_i_94003" </HT>


