<F P=100> West Europe </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sino-UK Adult Education Seminar Held in Jinan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sino-UK Adult Education Seminar Held in Jinan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1404093694 Beijing XINHUA in English 0842 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1404093694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Jinan, April 14 (XINHUA) -- The first Sino-British 
adult education seminar was held yesterday in Jinan, capital of 
east China's Shandong Province. 
  The seminar was co-sponsored by the Jinan-based Shandong 
Teacher's University (STU) and Nottingham College of Great 
Britain. 
  More than 80 educators from Britain, the United States, 
Canada, Australia, the Republic of Korea and China attended the 
seminar and presented some 60 papers, covering the management of 
adult education, relations between adult education and economic 
development, modes of adult education, education for rural 
population, lifetime education and experience in adult education. 
  The seminar will last for five days. 
  STU started an adult education program in 1956 and has 
trained about 20,000 adult students over the past 38 years. It 
has set up a college for adult education, which has an 
enrollment of more than 7,000 students. 
  In 1987 the university signed a cooperation agreement with 
Nottingham College in Sino-British adult education. 
  It is a cooperative and friendly conference, said Professor 
J. E. Thomas, vice-president of Nottingham College. He 
expressed the hope that every grown-up in the world will have 
the chance and freedom to read. 

</TEXT>

