<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Taipei, Riyadh To Step Up Economic Cooperation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Taipei, Riyadh To Step Up Economic Cooperation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1304142394 Taipei CNA in English 1320 GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1304142394 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Benjamin Yeh] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, April 13 (CNA) -- The 13th Economic Session 
of the Sino-Saudi Arabia Permanent Joint Committee on Economic 
and Technical Cooperation closed Wednesday [13 April], with the 
two sides pledging to step up bilateral economic and trade 
cooperation. 
  The two countries agreed to strengthen cooperation on 
transportation, shipping, agricultural, power, and 
telecommunications projects. 
  Vice Economic Affairs Minister S.J. Li and Ibrahim 
Bin-Salamah, a deputy minister and vice chairman of the Saudi 
Arabia Basic Industry Cooperation, inked the accord. 
  This was the first vice ministerial-level conference in 
Taipei since the two countries severed diplomatic relations in 
July 1990. 
  During two days of discussions, the two countries 
tentatively 
agreed to sign an investment guarantee pact and an agreement 
eliminating double taxation. 
  They also agreed to reduce tariffs, increase private 
exchanges, and clamp down on pirated computer software. 
  The committee will hold its next annual meeting in Riyadh, 
but the time has not yet been fixed. 

</TEXT>

