<F P=100> Science &amp; Technology </F>
<H3> <TI>   Institute Develops Technology for Chemical Industry </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Institute Develops Technology for Chemical Industry </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1304071594 Beijing XINHUA in English 0650 GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1304071594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Chengdu, April 13 (XINHUA) -- A research institute 
in Sichuan Province has developed an advanced technological 
process that greatly reduces industrial consumption of fuel and 
materials. 
  The "gas separation process by pressure swing absorption" 
(PSA) developed at the Southwest China Institute of Chemical 
Industry (SCICI) is being used in 270 chemical and other 
enterprises throughout China. 
  According to SCICI President Feng Xiaoting, these PSA 
installations consume 500 million kwh less electricity and 
600,000 tons less coal a year than the conventional cooling 
process. 
  That means an additional cut of one billion yuan in 
production cost for the enterprises. 
  In 1985, SCICI won the state scientific progress prize for 
developing the process and industrializing its use. "Nationwide 
application of the process is being promoted by the state 
commission for science and technology," Feng said. 
  "We concentrate on what is most urgently needed by the 
country and enterprises -- that's the secret of our success," he 
said, adding that since 1984, the institute has won national 
prizes for nine scientific accomplishments. 
  Next in importance to psa is a method that reduces use of 
natural gas from 1,200 cubic meters for producing a ton of 
ammonia to 850. 
  The method is specifically meant for synthetic ammonia 
plants 
with a production capacity of less than 50,000 tons a year. 
There are more than 1,000 such plants throughout China, 
including about 80 in Sichuan Province. 
  "If the method is used in all Sichuan plants, that will save 
an annual average of 400 million cubic meters of gas and 250 
million kwh of electricity," Feng said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

