<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shareholding Promotes Development in Pudong </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shareholding Promotes Development in Pudong </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1404025794 Beijing XINHUA in English 0244 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1404025794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Shanghai, April 14 (XINHUA) -- The shareholding 
system has become a new force in advancing the development of 
the Pudong area in East Shanghai. 
  In 1990, the central government approved the opening of 
China's first stock exchange center in Pudong. Now the center 
has 501 member companies, with 152 kinds of stocks listed. It 
became the country's largest stock market in 1993 when its 
business volume reached 500 billion yuan. 
  To date, 27 companies in Pudong have had their stocks 
listed. 
They raised 15 billion yuan through issuing stocks, relieving 
the fund shortage to some extent. 
  The Lujiazui financial and trade district is accelerating 
the 
construction of some one hundred commercial buildings and 
business centers. 
  The Jinqiao manufacturing district is also speeding up the 
official operation of close to a hundred projects and the 
construction of 200 other projects. The district is expected to 
become a new center of export-oriented industries. 
  Other listed companies at the Shanghai stock exchange center 
also value Pudong as a "golden area". More than half of these 
corporations have invested there, with the total sum exceeding 
10 billion yuan. 
  Some large companies listed at the Shenzhen stock exchange 
have also made inroads in Pudong. 

</TEXT>

