------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|waterway                 |24 million person/km     |-22.0                    | 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|air                      |1.529 billion person/km  |61.7                     | 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 


  Post and telecommunications undertakings developed rapidly. 
The province's business volume in post and telecommunications 
in 1993 totalled 558 million yuan, up 55.6 percent over the 
previous year. A total of 3,335 long-distance telephone lines 
were newly opened and there were 10,624 new subscribers during 
the whole year. 
  In the whole province, a total of 358,000 
urban telephone lines were recorded in 1993, 140,000 more than 
in the previous year. Of this, the number of program- 
controlled telephone lines reached 274,000, an increase of 
155,000. The province had a total capacity of 450,000 lines in 
its telephone networks, and the number of telephone sets reached 
346,200, with 86 cities above county level covered by an 
automated switching network of long-distance telephone lines and 
48 cities fitted with international direct dial telephones. 
Both the expansion of urban telephone capacity and the increase 
in long-distance telephone lines in 1993 were unprecedented. 
<H5>  . Domestic Trade and Market Prices </H5>
  The domestic consumer market was brisk and thriving. In 
1993, reform in the circulation field developed in depth, there 
was an abundance of consumer goods in the market, and market 
sales were brisk and stable, along with intensified and improved 
macroeconomic regulation and control exercised by the state. 
The retail sales volume of social commodities in the year 
totalled 29.5 billion yuan, up 25.8 percent over the previous 
year, or a real 5.8 percent increase after allowing for price 
rises. As viewed from commodity usage, retail sales of consumer 
goods amounted to 26.1 billion yuan, up 27.6 percent, and those 
of the means of agricultural production amounted to 3.4 billion 
yuan, up 13.3 percent. Of total retail sales of consumer goods, 
those in cities, county towns, and villages and towns below 
county level amounted to 11.6, 7.7, and 6.8 billion yuan, up 
43.2, 22.2, and 12.2 percent respectively over the previous 
year. As viewed from economic sectors, state-owned, collective, 
and individual units increased by 27.1, 22.0, and 27.4 percent 
respectively, and retail sales by peasants to nonagricultural 
residents also increased by 27.7 percent. As viewed from sales 
of major consumer goods, there were increases in some food 
categories and decreases in others, sales of clothing items 
mostly decreased except for fashionable clothes, articles for 
daily use mostly increased, and high-grade durables, including 
color television sets, washing machines, refrigerators, and so 
on increased substantially. The sales volume of major 
agricultural materials, such as chemical fertilizers, 
pesticides, and so on dropped to some extent compared with the 
previous year. 
  The contradiction between the supply and demand of the means 
of production was mitigated. Along with the slowdown of the 
rapidly growing momentum of fixed-assets investment, the 
marketing conditions for the major means of production, such as 
steel products, cement, and so on, which were in comparatively 
short supply for a time, underwent a change from 
panic-purchasing by buyers to the promotion of sales by 
suppliers, prices tended to stabilize, and stocks increased 
somewhat. In 1993, material supply and marketing enterprises 
bought 13.7 billion yuan worth of the means of production and 
sold 14.8 billion yuan, increasing by 33.1 and 38.5 percent 
respectively. Of the total, purchases of ferrous metals and 
building materials grew by 50.6 and 37.1 percent, and sales grew 
by 45.1 and 39.7 percent respectively. 
  Affected by factors including market demands, cost rises, 
and 
readjustment of prices out of policy consideration, market 
prices were fixed high and rose by large margins. Retail prices 
rose by 18.9 percent during the year, of which those in urban 
and rural areas rose by 16.3 and 20.2 percent respectively. 
Residents' costs of living rose by 21.3 percent, and those of 
urban and rural residents rose by 18.8 and 23.3 percent 
respectively. As a result, the lives of some residents 
receiving relatively lower income were somewhat affected. 
  The percentage of price increases with regard to various 
kinds of commodities in 1993 as compared with those in 1992 was 
as follows: 


