<H5>  6. Foreign Economic Exchange </H5>
  Remarkable achievements were made in foreign economic 
exchanges. In 1993, the province successfully hosted the First 
Kunming Trade Fair, further intensified economic and trade 
contacts with various countries, Southeast and South Asian 
countries and regions in particular. A new, open, 
world-oriented pattern with the vast territory of Southwest 
China as its backing, Kunming as a center, open border cities as 
forward positions, and Southeast and South Asia as focal points 
is taking shape. 
  Foreign trade grew steadily. In 1993, foreign trade 
enterprises continually advanced while overcoming difficulties 
in in-depth reform. According to statistics from the provincial 
economic and trade department, total imports and exports came to 
$840 million, an increase of 25.3 percent over the previous 
year. Of this, imports were $317 million and exports $523 
million, increases of 55.5 and 12.1 percent respectively. 
Spurred by reform and opening up, the export volume of 
machinery and electrical appliances increased substantially, 
with the total amount reaching $102.75 million, up 42 percent 
over 1992. Border trade grew by a wide margin, with its imports 
and exports totalling 2.873 billion yuan in 1993, up 26.6 
percent over the previous year. 
  The tourist industry thrived. In 1993, a total of 405,200 
people including foreign guests, overseas Chinese, and Hong 
Kong, Macao, and Taiwan compatriots came to visit Yunnan, an 
increase of 29.3 percent over the previous year. Foreign 
exchange earned from tourism amounted to $104 million, up 53.8 
percent. 
  A substantial amount of foreign capital was attracted. The 
year 1993 witnessed the greatest amount of foreign capital 
imported from abroad, and foreign capital actually utilized in 
the year was $187.95 million, 2.8 times more than the previous 
year. Of the total, direct foreign investment and foreign loans 
amounted to $97.02 million and $90.93 million, increasing 3.2 
and 3.3 times respectively. During the year, 509 
foreign-invested enterprises were approved for business 
registration. 
  Satisfactory achievements were attained in foreign economic 
and technological cooperation. During the year, $41.02 million 
worth of contracts for overseas construction projects and labor 
services were signed, up 1.7 times over the previous year, and 
business volume of $25.87 million was realized, up 74.1 percent. 
<H5>  7. Science, Technology, Education, Culture, Public Health, </H5>
and Sports 
  Gratifying achievements were scored in scientific and 
technological undertakings. During the year, the province won 
one prize for scientific and technological progress and two 
Spark prizes at the national level, as well as 193 prizes for 
scientific and technological progress and 30 Spark prizes at the 
provincial level. The relevant authority received 729 patent 
applications, and 686 of them were approved, up 100 percent over 
the previous year. During the year, 4,322 technical and 
economic contracts were signed with an amount of 170 million 
yuan transacted, up 40.9 percent over the previous year. 
Scientific and technological units transferred 602 of their 
research results to industrial enterprises for 41.35 million 
yuan. In 1993, the province approved the establishment of one 
state-level key laboratory, three provincial-level key 
laboratories, one state-level technological engineering research 
and development center, one provincial-level intermediate 
experimental base, and one state-level development zone. 
  New progress was made in education. In 1993, the province's 
educational institutions enrolled 275 postgraduates, up 38.9 
percent over the previous year, and the total number of students 
taking graduate courses was 612, up 15 percent over 1992. 
Enrollment of undergraduates in ordinary universities and 
colleges was 16,400, an increase of 8.2 percent, and the total 
number of enrolled students was 49,600, an increase of 9.3 
percent. Secondary vocational and technical education continued 
to develop. There were 191,900 students studying in various 
types of specialized secondary schools (including vocational 
secondary schools), up 6.6 percent over the previous year. 
Basic education progressed steadily. There were 1,089,400 
students in junior secondary schools and 4,438,800 pupils in 
primary schools across the province, up 3.6 and 0.4 percent 
respectively. The enrollment rate of school-age children 
reached 96.3 percent, and 67.7 percent of primary school 
graduates continued in secondary school, compared with 66.5 
percent in the previous year. Adult education developed 
relatively rapidly, with various kinds of technical training 
forging ahead in a comprehensive way. Enrollment of students 
studying in institutions of adult higher education was 11,400, 
up 29.6 percent over the previous year. Enrolled students in 
adult secondary vocational and technical schools were 29,800, an 
increase of 17.6 percent, and those in junior adult schools 
numbered 343,500, an increase of 15.7 percent. Illiteracy was 
eradicated among 260,000 people during the year. 
  Cultural undertakings continued to flourish. By the end of 
1993, there were 5,681 projection units of various kinds, 135 
art performance troupes, 128 cultural centers, 148 public 
libraries, 22 museums, 160 archives, 13 radio broadcasting 
stations, 41 medium and short-wave radio transmission and relay 
stations, 15 television stations, 27 television transmission and 
relay stations with a capacity of more than 1,000 watts each, 
and 10,600 ground stations for satellite televisions. During 
the year, the province produced two feature movies and two 
documentary movies, and the provincial film company distributed 
197 movies of various types. In addition, the province 
published 272 million copies of newspapers, 13.05 million copies 
of various magazines, and 117 million copies of books. 
  Public health undertakings advanced steadily. By the end of 
1993, there were 82,500 hospital beds and 107,700 specialized 
public health workers and technicians in the province, up 2.1 
and 1.9 percent respectively over the figure at the end of 1992, 
of whom 55,500 were doctors of traditional Chinese medicine, an 
increase of 3.7 percent. 
  Gratifying progress was made in sports. In 1993, mass 
athletic activities were widely conducted, and the province's 
athletes won five gold medals and one silver medal in 
international competitions. In national games (including 
national tournaments), they won 20 gold medals, 19 silver 
medals, and 24 bronze medals. During the year, an athlete broke 
a world record and two broke Asian records, and they gained 
honors for the country and province. 
  8. Population and Living Standards 
  According to a sample survey on population changes, the 
province's birth rate in 1993 was 22 per thousand, the death 
rate was 8.1 per thousand, and the natural growth rate was 13.9 
per thousand. Calculated on this basis, the total population of 
the province at the end of 1993 was 38.852 million people, 
536,000 more than the 1992 year-end figure. Residents' income 
grew steadily. According to a sample survey, the annual 
per-capita income of urban residents, used as living expenses, 
was 2,376 yuan, an increase of 8.2 percent over the previous 
year after allowing for price rises, and peasants' per-capita 
net income was 675 yuan, 57 yuan more than in 1992, or a 1.3 
percent increase after allowing for price rises due to payments 
for commodities. 
  Residents' savings continued to grow. By the end of 1993, 
the balance of urban and rural residents' savings deposits stood 
at 25.123 billion yuan, or 28.3 percent more than the figure at 
the end of 1992. Their awareness of financial investments was 
enhanced, and their purchases of various negotiable securities 
such as stocks, bonds, and others also increased noticeably. 
  Rapid development was attained in insurance services. In 
1993, premiums for various kinds of insurance throughout the 
province amounted to 139.297 billion yuan, up 51.8 percent over 
the previous year. Income earned from insurance business was 
953 million yuan, up 69.2 percent. Of the total, premiums for 
domestic property insurance amounted to 79.957 billion yuan, up 
27.4 percent, and income from insurance business in this area 
was 501 million yuan, up 57 percent. Throughout the province, 
there were 16,900 enterprises and institutions participating in 
enterprise property insurance programs, 3,957,300 families in 
family property insurance programs, and 6,505,500 individuals in 
life insurance programs. Insurance companies took 102,600 
claims for property losses and paid an indemnity of 264 million 
yuan for settled cases. They also paid 20.89 million yuan to 
276,600 people as reparations in life insurance programs. 
  Living conditions for urban and rural residents improved 
further. In 1993, new residences covering an area of 5.19 
million square meters were built in cities and towns, while 
16.12 million square meters of new houses were built in rural 
areas. 
  Social welfare undertakings developed with each passing day. 
In 1993, there were 15,400 beds in 729 social welfare 
institutions of various types across the province with 10,924 
occupants. A total of 4,766,000 urban and rural residents 
received various kinds of social relief from the state. 
  New progress was also made in environmental protection. By 
the end of 1993, there were 1,666 people working in the 
province's environmental protection department and its 
affiliated organs. There were also 84 environment monitoring 
stations at various levels and four nature reserves at national 
level. During the year, 76 projects for the rectification of 
environment pollution within fixed periods were completed, with 
a total investment amount of 40.39 million yuan. By the end of 
1993, 29 soot-control zones were established in four cities, 
covering an area of 107 square km, and 19 noise-control zones 
were established in two cities, covering an area of 29 square km. 
  Notes: 1. All figures quoted in this communique are 
preliminary. 2. GNP and value added by various industries 
chiefly include laborers' wages, profits, taxes, depreciation, 
and so on, but exclude various kinds of intermediate 
  consumption values, including energy, raw and semifinished 
materials, and so on. The absolute amounts are calculated at 
current prices, whereas growth rates are at comparable 
prices. 3. Base-year figures are official statistics from the 
Yunnan Statistical Yearbook. 

</TEXT>

