<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Spokesman Holds News Briefing </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry Spokesman Holds News Briefing </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Says Wei Case Not Human Rights Issue </H4>

<F P=102> HK1404085494 Hong Kong AFP in English 0828 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> HK1404085494 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 14 (AFP)--China's most celebrated 
dissident Wei Jingsheng is a criminal whose current detention 
and investigation should not be confused with the issue of human 
rights in China, a foreign ministry spokesman said Thursday [14 
April]. "The case of Wei Jingsheng is by no means an issue of 
human rights," spokesman Shen Guofang told a weekly press 
briefing. "Human rights does not simply mean releasing a 
criminal, which is totally irrelevant to human rights," Shen 
added. 
  The spokesman's remarks fuelled speculation that Wei may 
face 
fresh criminal charges following his arrest April 1. The 
Chinese authorities have said Wei, who was released in September 
six months shy of a 15-year jail term for 
"counter-revolutionary" activities, is currently being 
investigated for "suspected new crimes." No official charges 
have yet been brought against the 43-year-old dissident. 
  Shen made similar distinctions concerning the brief 
detentions of pro-democracy activists in Beijing and Shanghai 
during the recent visit of French Prime Minister Edouard 
Balladur. "They are not democracy activists. They are 
criminals, most of whom are still on parole. 
  "Therefore, during such parole the Chinese legal authorities 
have every right to take action," Shen said, adding that the 
detentions "had nothing to do with the visit (of Balladur)." 
However, of the four dissidents detained during the French 
prime minister's visit -- Xu Wenli, Wang Fucheng, Bao Ge and 
Yang Zhou -- only Xu is still currently on parole. 
  Shen also said the Chinese authorities were having 
difficulties handling lists of political prisoners handed over 
for their consideration during visits here by foreign 
dignitaries such as US Secretary of State Warren Christopher. 
"After some investigation, we found a lot of problems with such 
lists. Some people simply do not exist and some people have 
already been released," Shen said. "We often check the contents 
of such lists with those visiting leaders and we found that even 
they did not have a clear idea about the source of such lists 
and the people named in them," he added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

