<F P=100> Central-South Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hainan Statistical Communique for 1993 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hainan Statistical Communique for 1993 </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK1204050894 Haikou HAINAN RIBAO in Chinese 28 Feb 94 p 6 </F>
<F P=103> HK1204050894 </F>
<F P=104>  Haikou HAINAN RIBAO </F>
<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Communique issued by the Hainan Provincial Statistics </F>
Bureau on 23 February 1994: "Statistical Report Issued by 
Hainan Provincial Statistics Bureau on National Economic and 
Social Development in 1993"] 
  [Text] In 1993, under the correct leadership of the Hainan 
Provincial CPC Committee and the Hainan Provincial Government, 
people of various ethnic groups in Hainan Province seriously 
implemented the spirit of the 14th CPC Congress and the Third 
Plenary Session of the 14th CPC Central Committee and various 
policies laid down by the Central Committee on speeding up the 
development and construction of Hainan Province. Closely 
centering around building the system of a socialist market 
economy, they increased the strength of reforms, expanded 
opening to the outside world, and quickened the pace of 
construction. The national economy made sustained, rapid, and 
healthy development, the economic structure was readjusted to 
some extent, economic strength was further enhanced, and the 
living standard of the people kept rising. Science, technology, 
culture, education, public health, and various other social 
undertakings achieved success. According to preliminary 
calculations, the gross domestic product (GDP) of the whole 
province might reach 20.413 billion yuan, calculated by 
comparable price, an increase of 22.8 percent over that of the 
previous year. In GDP, primary industry grew by 10.5 percent, 
secondary industry by 51.6 percent, and tertiary industry by 
15.3 percent. The growth rate was much faster than the national 
average, which laid a foundation for Hainan's economic and 
social development to further enter a new stage. 
  Major problems in economic operations were: Prominent 
"bottleneck" constraints in basic industries and infrastructure, 
weak agricultural foundation, slow growth of the peasants' 
income, a big margin of prices increase, incomplete tourist 
facilities, and a reduction in the number of international 
visitors. 
<H5>  I. Agriculture </H5>
  Agricultural production grew rapidly and in a sustained 
manner. In 1993, the agricultural added value of the whole 
province amounted to 7.552 billion yuan, an increase of 10.5 
percent over that of the previous year calculated at comparable 
prices. There was an overall development in agriculture, 
forestry, animal husbandry, and fishery, and major improvement 
in agricultural internal structure. The proportion of animal 
husbandry and fishery in total agricultural output rose from 
32.6 percent of the previous year to 35.6 percent. The added 
value of agriculture, forestry, animal husbandry, and fishery 
was as follows: 


------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|                         |1993                     |Percentage increase or d-| 
|                         |                         |ecrease over 1992        | 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|Agriculture              |3.421 billion yuan       |2.7                      | 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|Forestry                 |1.699 billion yuan       |6.2                      | 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|Animal husbandry         |1.435 billion yuan       |26.5                     | 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|Fishery                  |997 million yuan         |23.1                     | 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 


  In the output of major agricultural products, areas sown 
with 
cereals and sugar canes were reduced and their output dropped as 
a result of drought. The output of oil-bearing crops, 
vegetables, melons, and vegetables all reached an all-time high, 
and especially the output of vegetables, bananas, and mangoes 
increased by a big margin. Scale performance was achieved on a 
preliminary basis, which helped the growing industry develop 
toward the direction of high yield and top quality. Output of 
major agricultural products was as follows: 


