|end                      |                         |                         | 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 


  Fishery production entered a new stage. In 1993, the total 
output of aquatic products in the whole province amounted to 
324,400 tons, an increase of 26.1 percent over the previous 
year, in which the output of marine products amounted to 287,700 
tons, up by 28.1 percent. Aquatic breeding area totalled 40,300 
hectares, an increase of 300 hectares over the previous year. 
  Construction of water conservancy work continued to be 
strengthened, and there was new improvement in the conditions of 
agricultural production. In 1993, cultivated area under 
effective irrigation in the whole province totalled 175,100 
hectares, and the amount of electricity used in the rural areas 
totalled 120.50 million kwh, an increase of 4.7 percent over 
that of the previous year. The amount of chemical fertilizer 
applied for agricultural use (conversion net) totalled 146,500 
tons, a reduction of 2.5 percent from that of the previous year, 
and the total power of agricultural machines amounted to 1.585 
million kw, an increase of 7.6 percent over the previous year, 
in which the power of irrigation machines for agricultural use 
grew by 7.7 percent, and the power of fishery machines grew by 
14.1 percent. 
  Nonagricultural industries in the rural areas developed 
rapidly, and industrial restructuring made major progress. In 
1993, output of nonagricultural industries in the whole province 
amounted to 3.702 billion yuan, an increase of 90.6 percent over 
that of the previous year (incomparable factors of prices 
increase included, the same below), in which rural industry grew 
by 1.6 times, building industry grew by 53.6 percent, industry 
of communications and transportation by 53.3 percent, commerce 
and food and drink by 45.0 percent, and the growth margin was 
faster than that of total agricultural output. A part of rural 
labor was shifted toward secondary industry and tertiary 
industry. At the end of 1993, rural labor engaged in secondary 
industry and tertiary industry in the whole province amounted to 
357,200 people, an increase of 62,500 people over the end of the 
previous year. 
<H5>  II. Industry </H5>
  Industrial production grew rapidly. In 1993, the industrial 
added value of the whole province reached 2.810 billion yuan, an 
increase of 36.2 percent over the previous year, in which the 
industrial added value of the township level and above amounted 
to 2.483 billion yuan, up 32.4 percent. 
  There was overall growth in various economic-type 
industries. 
In the industrial added value of the whole province in 1993, 
added value of state-owned industries amounted to 1.612 billion 
yuan, an increase of 12.1 percent over the previous year. The 
added value of collective ownership industries amounted to 144 
million yuan, an increase of 34.8 percent over the previous 
year, and the added value of other economic-type industries 
amounted to 727 million yuan, an increase of 119.9 percent over 
the previous year, in which the added value of foreign-funded 
enterprises grew by 86.1 percent. The proportion of added value 
which foreign-funded enterprises occupied in industrial added 
value of the whole province rose from 13.6 percent the previous 
year to 18.3 percent. 
  Both light and heavy industries grew rapidly. Pulled by 
investment demand, the growth of heavy industry was faster than 
that of light industry, and readjustments were made in both the 
light and heavy industrial structure. In 1993, the added value 
of light industry in the whole province amounted to 1.867 
billion yuan, an increase of 30.4 percent over the previous 
year. The added value of heavy industry amounted to 943 million 
yuan, an increase of 49.4 percent over the previous year. In 
total industrial output value, the proportion of heavy industry 
rose from 34.7 percent of the previous year to 38.6 percent, and 
the proportion of light industry dropped from 65.3 percent of 
the previous year to 61.4 percent. 
  In the output of major industrial products, investment 
products such as steel products, automobiles, cement, and 
artificial boards, and light industrial products that relied on 
technical progress such as canned food, drinks, and cigarettes, 
grew rapidly. Electric energy production and motorcycles 
increased by a big margin. The output of major industrial 
products was as follows: 


