  Propelled by consumer demand, market prices grew by a big 
margin. In 1993 the overall retail price level of the whole 
society (including consumer goods of living and agricultural 
means of production) rose by an average of 23.9 percent over the 
previous year; in cities and towns it rose by 24.2 percent; and 
in rural areas it rose by 19.1 percent. The overall price level 
of the residents' cost of living (including consumer goods of 
living and service items) rose by an average of 23.3 percent 
over the previous year; in cities and towns it rose by 23.7 
percent; and in rural areas it rose by 16.5 percent. 
