<H5>  VI. Foreign Trade, Economic Cooperation, and Tourism </H5>
  In 1993 our province developed the "Hainan International 
Solicit Business Year" activities, successfully held "two 
celebrations" (the fifth anniversary of the founding of Hainan 
Province and the Second Hainan International Coconut Festival) 
and "three fairs" (the 1993 Hainan Export Commodity Fair, the 
Third Hainan Folks Friendship Fair, and Hainan Science and 
Technology Fair), and achieved success in issuing 80 million 
dollar bonds outside China for the first time, which effectively 
promoted the development of Hainan's foreign economic 
cooperation and tourist business. 
  Import and export trade maintained a rising momentum. In 
1993, total import and export value of the whole province 
reached 2.569 billion dollars, an increase of 51.7 percent over 
the previous year, and total foreign trade export value amounted 
to 902 million dollars, up by 2.3 percent. Total port export 
value amounted to 1.667 billion dollars, an increase of 1.05 
times. 
  The province achieved remarkable success in soliciting 
business and introducing foreign capital in 1993. Hainan 
Province took the lead in carrying out the direct enterprise 
registration system and simplifying investment approval 
procedures, actively drew close to international practice, and 
achieved notable results. In the whole year, a total of 3,106 
foreign business investment contracts were approved, an increase 
of 68.4 percent over the previous year. The contracted use of 
foreign capital totalled 6.423 billion dollars, an increase of 
81.1 percent over the previous year, and the actual use of 
foreign capital totalled 972 million dollars, an increase of 
82.7 percent. Among foreign business investment contracts 
approved in the whole year, 3,091 contracts were direct 
investments by overseas investors, an increase of 68.9 percent 
over the previous year, their direct investments stipulated in 
contracts totalled 5.607 billion dollars, up by 74.4 percent, 
and actual use of their direct investments amounted to 734 
million dollars, up by 62.4 percent. 
  As of the end of 1993, a total of 7,269 foreign business 
investment enterprises had their registrations approved by 
Hainan industry and commerce management departments, with a 
subscription of 10.04 billion dollars of registered capital. 
  Tourism continued to develop. By the end of 1993, Hainan 
province had a total of 96 tourist hotels and guest houses for 
overseas visitors, and among them, 23 were assessed as 
star-grade, i.e., three hotels were assessed as four star, nine 
hotels three star, six hotels two star, and five hotels one 
star, with a total of 17,900 beds, an increase of 3.1 percent 
over the previous year. 
  There were some increases in the number of visitors. In 
1993, hotels and guest houses for overseas visitors hosted a 
total of 2,794,100 overnight stays, an increase of 13 percent 
over the previous year. They hosted 2,554,400 overnight stays 
by domestic visitors, up 15.9 percent; 239,700 overnight stays 
by overseas visitors, a reduction of 11.2 percent; 139,300 
overnight stays by compatriots from Hong Kong and Macao, a 
reduction of 21.2 percent; and stays by foreigners and 
compatriots from Taiwan grew by 6.9 percent and 14.6 percent 
respectively. The rate of accommodation of hotels and guest 
houses for overseas visitors was 74.3 percent, an increase of 
one percentage point over the previous year. Foreign exchange 
income from tourism amounted to 352 million yuan (FEC), an 
increase of 13.2 percent over the previous year; income from 
commodities totalled 272 million yuan, up 10.3 percent; and 
income from labor was 80 million yuan, up 23.9 percent. 
<H5>  VII. Science, Technology, Education, Culture, and Physical </H5>
Culture 
  There was overall development in scientific and 
technological 
undertakings. In 1993, scientific and technological departments 
of Hainan Province arranged three state-level Torch Plan 
projects, seven Spark Plan projects, 24 provincial-level Torch 
Plan projects, and 12 provincial Spark Plan projects, arranged 
seven state-level key task projects and 13 provincial-level 
scientific and technological plan projects. They approved 
setting up 26 provincial natural science foundation projects, 
and examined and approved seven local matching projects 
subsidized by the state-level natural science foundation. "High 
performance soil solidifying agents" were evaluated as an 
"All-China Torch Plan Excellent Project," a "zinc oxide 
pressure-sensing resistor" and other two state-level Torch 
projects and "renal failure tranquilizer development and 
application" for treating renal failure and other two provincial 
level Torch projects were evaluated as state-level new key 
products. Thirty-two awards for 1993 Science and Technology 
Progress were evaluated by provincial scientific and 
technological departments, among them were two first grade 
awards, five second grade awards, 11 third grade awards, and 17 
fourth grade awards. Three provincial level Spark awards were 
evaluated, among them one third grade award, and two fourth 
grade awards. 
  In 1993, the province handled 170 patent applications, an 
increase of five applications over the previous year. 105 
patents were authorized, an increase of 1.7 times over the 
previous year. Eight patent technological items were carried 
out, with 121 million yuan of tax and profit earnings. 
  The technology market was increasingly brisk. In 1993 Hainan 
Province technology market management departments confirmed and 
registered 17 technical contracts, with a total contract amount 
of 9.135 million yuan. "The Second Hainan International Coconut 
Festival Technology and Trade Talk" and "Hainan Science and 
Technology Fair" held by the province yielded good results. 
There were major developments in scientific and technological 
exchanges and cooperation. The provincial scientific and 
technological departments received several scientific and 
technological delegations from foreign countries, and carried 
out four projects of international scientific and technological 
cooperation. 
  The scientific and technological contingent grew unceasingly 
in strength. By the end of 1993, state-owned enterprises and 
public undertakings in the whole province totalled 112,200 
various kinds of technicians, among them, 3,282 had senior 
titles, and 24,900 had intermediate titles. 
  Various educational undertakings further developed. The 
enrollment scale of universities and colleges continuously 
expanded. In 1993, six general institutions of higher learning 
in the whole province enrolled 3,413 undergraduates and students 
in specialized subjects, an increase of 9.2 percent over those 
of the previous year, with a total number of 10,232 students, up 
by 20.4 percent; twenty secondary technological schools in the 
whole province enrolled 3,952 students, up 31.0 percent, with a 
total number of 8,908 students, up 20.0 percent. Eight 
secondary teacher-training schools enrolled 2,828 students, an 
increase of 51.2 percent, with a total number of 5,898 students, 
up 25.8 percent. Twelve skilled worker schools enrolled 2,269 
students, an increase of 17.4 percent, with a total number of 
4,918 students, up 22.2 percent. General senior middle schools 
enrolled 15,057 students, dropping by 9.8 percent, with a total 
number of 44,186 students, dropping 14.4 percent. Occupational 
senior middle schools enrolled 3,907 students, a reduction of 
5.9 percent, with a total number of 9,047 students, dropping 
11.3 percent. 
  In 1993 there were 229,900 students in general junior middle 
schools in the whole province, an increase of 9.4 percent over 
the previous year; there were 1,067,300 pupils in primary 
schools, an increase of 3 percent over the previous year; and 
126,400 children were in kindergartens, an increase of 10.9 
percent over the previous year. The rate of school age children 
entering schools was 99 percent, and the proportion of primary 
school graduates entering schools of a higher grade was 81.6 
percent. 
  Adult education developed extensively in 1993. Adult 
institutions of higher learning in the whole province enrolled 
1,645 students, an increase of 74.4 percent over the previous 
year, with a total number of 2,923 students, up 7.6 percent. 
Adult secondary schools enrolled 6,066 students, an increase of 
40.7 percent over the previous year, with a total number of 
9,678 students, up by 2.3 percent. There were 42,100 students 
in adult primary and secondary schools, an increase of 7.0 
percent over the previous year, and there were 121,600 students 
in adult technical training schools. 
  Culture and art, broadcasting and television, news and 
publications flourished in 1993. There were 22 various kinds of 
art performance troupes across the province, 17 cultural halls, 
three mass art museums, 19 public libraries, 296 township and 
town cultural stations, 110 country fair cultural centers, 25 
archives, 19 broadcasting stations, five TV stations, and 22 TV 
transmission and relay stations. A total of 11 TV operas in 53 
volumes were shot in the whole year, among which the 8-volume TV 
opera "Poet Mao Zedong" evoked fine social repercussions. The 
province had a total of five books and audiovisual publishing 
organizations, 17 newspapers, and 37 magazines, and published a 
total of 21.37 million copies of 518 different books and 14 
kinds of newspapers, with a total distribution of 104.75 million 
copies. Thirty-one kinds of magazines in 3.39 million copies 
came off the press, and 480,000 videocassettes were published. 
Liangshan county seat was approved as a historical and cultural 
famous city of China, and the former residence of Qiujun and 18 
other cultural relics preservation units were approved to be 
state-level major cultural relics preservation units. 
  Physical cultural undertakings achieved good results. In 
1993 a total of 226 sports meets at the county level and above 
were held in the whole province, 17 provincial sports 
competitions were held, and 221 athletes were selected to take 
part in 17 various kinds of nationwide competitions. The 
province organized athletes for the first time to take part in 
15 competitions in the Seventh All-China National Games, and won 
one gold medal and one bronze medal. In nationwide teenager 
single-item competitions, 21 first place awards were won, and 
646,000 people reached the state physical training standards in 
1993. 
<H5>  VIII. Public Health and Environmental Protection </H5>
  Public health undertakings made steady development, and 
medical conditions were further improved. In 1993, various 
kinds of medical and public health institutions in the whole 
province had a total of 22,800 hospital beds, an increase of 1.9 
percent over the previous year, and there were 30,500 various 
kinds of public health workers, an increase of 0.5 percent. 
Among them were 940 doctors of traditional Chinese medicine, 
6,333 doctors of western medicine, 8,618 practitioners of both 
Chinese and western medicine, 7,236 nursing masters and nurses, 
and 589 midwives. Public health and epidemic prevention work 
achieved good results. The incidence of infectious diseases in 
the whole province dropped by 10.7 percent compared with the 
previous year. In the year, public health and epidemic 
prevention departments developed activities for prevention and 
treatment of polio, and achieved good results. 
  Environmental resources protection continued to be 
strengthened, and the policy of closely combining economic 
development with environmental resources protection was carried 
out. In 1993, the whole province completed 68 pollution control 
projects, and the industrial waste water processing rate was 
41.9 percent, the industrial waste gas processing rate was 80.4 
percent, and the industrial dust handling rate was 57.0 percent. 
The rate of simultaneous implementation of "three-pollution 
control" for construction projects completed and put into 
operation the same year was 89.9 percent. By the end of the 
year, the province had a total of 20 environmental monitoring 
stations. 
  At the end of 1993, the whole province had 1,225,100 
hectares 
of forest area (tropical forest included), and forest coverage 
reached 35.6 percent. 
  In 1993, Hainan Province possessed 102 species of wild 
animals and 55 species of wild plants under major state 
preservation, and 78 various kinds of natural reserves, among 
them were five state-level and 25 provincial-level natural 
reserves. Of natural reserves, 68 were land natural reserves 
with an area of 142,200 hectares. 
<H5>  IX. Population, Labor, and the Life of the People </H5>
  According to a sample survey of population changes, the 
birth 
rate in Hainan Province in 1993 was 20.81 per thousand, dropping 
by 0.50 per thousand point compared to the previous year, and 
the mortality rate was 5.26 per thousand, dropping by 0.81 per 
thousand. The natural growth rate was 15.55 per thousand, up 
0.31 per thousand. Based on the above calculation, total 
population of the whole province reached 7,011,600 at the end of 
the year, an increase of 147,600 people over those at the end of 
the previous year. 
  Labor employment continued to expand in reform of the 
employment system and social insurance system. In 1993, Hainan 
Province acquired 7,900 university and college graduates, an 
increase of 19.7 percent over the previous year. By the end of 
the year, the province had a total of 1,113,200 staff and 
workers, with 983,800 of them working in state-owned units, 
among whom contract-based staff and workers accounted for 27.4 
percent. 
  Occupation recommendation services were just unfolding. In 
1993 the whole province had 51 occupation recommendation 
institutions, four of which were run by people with affirmed 
qualifications. These institutions accepted the registrations of 
28,800 people looking for jobs, with 9,800 people successfully 
finding employment through recommendations. The establishment 
of the social insurance system was making smooth progress. By 
the end of the year, 732,200 staff and workers in the whole 
province were covered in old-age insurance, 468,700 were covered 
in wait-for-employment insurance, 329,900 in industrial injury 
insurance, and 14,200 in medical care insurance. 
  Income of urban and rural residents increased. Gross wages 
of staff and workers in the whole province amounted to 3.467 
billion yuan, an increase of 15.3 percent over the previous 
year. Per capita income of total staff and workers was 3,115 
yuan, an increase of 15.3 percent over the previous year. 
According to a sample survey of urban and rural resident 
families, the cost-of-living income of city and town residents 
was 2,774 yuan per capita, an increase of 32.5 percent over the 
previous year. With price rise factors deducted, actual growth 
was 7.1 percent. Net income of the peasants was 1.016 yuan per 
capita, an increase of 13.9 percent over that of the previous 
year, in which net productive income was 883 yuan, an increase 
of 13.6 percent over the previous year. But, due to the impact 
of price rises, a number of low-income resident families in 
urban and rural areas were leading a difficult life, and annual 
per capita net income of 13.3 percent of the rural population 
was below 500 yuan. 
  There was a steady increase in savings in urban and rural 
areas. At the end of the year, balance of savings deposits (city 
credit cooperative savings and postal savings included) of urban 
and rural residents in the whole province reached 18.402 billion 
yuan, calculated by comparable specifications, an increase of 
63.2 percent over that at the end of the previous year. There 
were new changes in the property make-up of the residents' 
deposits, securities, and house properties. 
  Housing construction in urban and rural areas further 
developed. In 1993, the newly built area of residential flats 
completed in urban and rural areas totalled 2,094,700 square 
meters, and commodity residential flats totalled 462,900 square 
meters. Newly built private residential flats completed in 
rural areas totalled 1,565,900 square meters. 
  Notes: 
  (1) Gross domestic product (GDP) and various absolute 
figures of added values listed in the communique are calculated 
by current prices, and growth rate is calculated by comparable 
prices. 
  (2) Nonagricultural industries in rural areas refer to 
rural industry, rural building industry, rural transportation 
industry, rural commerce, and food and drink business. 
  (3) Absolute figures of output of nonagricultural 
industries in rural areas are calculated by current prices, and 
prices rise factor is not yet deducted from growth rate. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

