<F P=100> Near East &amp; South Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dhaka Radio Reports Meeting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Dhaka Radio Reports Meeting </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1504033494 Dhaka Radio Bangladesh Network in English 0130 
GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1504033494 </F>
<F P=104>  Dhaka Radio Bangladesh Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Chinese Prime Minister Li Peng has said he would 
like to visit Bangladesh in the later half of the year. He said 
this during his meeting in Beijing yesterday with the visiting 
Bangladeshi Foreign Minister A.S.M. Mustafizur Rahman. The 
Chinese premier was responding to a letter of invitation from 
Prime Minister Begum Khaleda Zia that was handed over to him by 
the Bangladeshi foreign minister. The date for the visit will 
be worked out through normal diplomatic channels. 
  Mr. Li Peng said Bangladesh and China enjoy traditional 
relations which are excellent and that the two countries have no 
problems whatsoever. Mr. Mustafizur Rahman conveyed to Premier 
Li Peng greetings of Prime Minister Begum Khaleda Zia. He said 
China is one of the first countries Begum Zia visited in 1991 to 
manifest the confidence that Bangladesh has in its friendship 
with China. The Bangladeshi foreign minister said his country 
is looking forward to China's role in helping Asian countries 
achieve economic development. 
  Mr. Mustafiz also briefed the Chinese premier about the 
efforts of Bangladesh as chairperson of SAARC [South Asian 
Association for Regional Cooperation] to develop regional 
cooperation. He raised Bangladesh's problem with India relating 
to sharing of water of the Ganges and Tista and the situation 
relating to Myanmar refugees where China's [words indistinct] 
support is helpful. 

</TEXT>

