<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Enterprises To Invest $2 Billion in Indonesia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Enterprises To Invest $2 Billion in Indonesia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1304043594 Taipei Voice of Free China in English 0200 GMT 
12 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW1304043594 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei Voice of Free China </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "News" program] </F>
  [Text] A ranking economic official said that state-run 
enterprises are expected to funnel a total of approximately $2 
billion of investment into Indonesia in the coming three years, 
part of the effort to comply with the government's go-south 
investment policy. Vice Economic Minister S.J. Lee made these 
remarks at a press conference held after his return to Taiwan 
from a 9-day trip to Indonesia as the leader of the 33-member 
Taipei delegation. The group comprised senior executives from 
state-run enterprises under the jurisdiction of the Ministry of 
Economic Affairs. Lee said his ministry will try to speed up 
efforts to materialize the go-south investment policy, greatly 
advocated by both President Li and Premier Lien, by helping 
government-owned and private enterprises with investments in 
Southeast Asian countries, especially Indonesia, Vietnam, and 
the Philippines. During the 9-day stay in Indonesia, senior 
executives of seven state-run enterprises and their Indonesian 
counterparts reached a consensus on 13 joint venture investments 
and technical cooperation projects. 

</TEXT>

